      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip — ~ 8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym- or home-gym lighting, neutral or soft background; outfit simple workout clothes; soft key-light + ambient fill so posture and leg-motion are clear\n* Sound: Soft ambient (floor contact, subtle breath, minimal ambient noise), no voice-over (or optionally soft inhale-exhale cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Stable floor, enough space to take a split stance (one foot forward, one foot back) — can be done in home-gym, gym floor, or even living-room with enough room.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) capturing full body from head to feet, so stance, knee-hip motion, torso posture, foot placement all visible.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, wearing workout clothes (tank or tee + shorts/ pants), ready in staggered stance — one leg forward, one leg back, torso upright, core engaged.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s — Setup: Subject stands in a staggered stance: one foot forward (working leg), other foot behind (rear leg), distance such that when lowering, the front thigh and rear leg can bend comfortably. Hands can be at hips or holding dumbbells at sides (if weighted). Core is braced, chest up, back straight.\n* 1 s–2 s — Brace & prepare: Engage core, keep gaze forward (or slightly down), ensure balance is stable. Front foot planted firmly, weight distributed through foot (not toes), rear foot supporting balance lightly.\n* 2 s–4 s — Descent / Lowering phase: Bend knees and hips to lower body — lower your hips until front thigh is roughly parallel to floor (or as your mobility allows), rear knee lowers toward floor (without resting hard), torso remains upright, front knee tracks over foot.\n* 4 s–5 s — Bottom / Hold: Pause at bottom ~0.2–0.5 s; feel stretch/engagement in front thigh & glute/hip area, core tight, balance maintained.\n* 5 s–7 s — Ascent / Stand up: Push through the front foot heel/entire foot, extend knee and hip to return to starting upright split stance. Rear leg remains stable; keep posture upright, core engaged.\n* 7 s–8 s — Reset / Ready position: Fully upright in split stance, breathing controlled, ready for next rep or fade-out clip.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Quadriceps (front thigh) and Gluteus maximus (glutes/hips) — main drivers of knee extension and hip extension during the movement.\n* Secondary / Supporting: Hamstrings, hip-adductors/abductors, calves (for stability), and core/obliques (for balance, stability, posture).\nBenefits & Why Use Split Squat\n* Unilateral leg strength & balance: Because you work one leg at a time, split squats help even out strength imbalances and enhance stability.\n* Quad and glute development: Effective for building strength, muscle, and endurance in thighs and glutes — ideal for lower-body strength, aesthetics, and functional power (walking, jumping, running).\n* Core and stability engagement: The staggered stance and balance requirement activate core and stabilizing muscles, improving posture and control.\n* Joint and mobility benefits: Works hips, knees, ankles through range of motion — can aid mobility, flexibility and joint control when done properly.\n* Alternative to bilateral squats: Easier to manage for people who want lower-body training with less spinal load or when equipment is limited.\nForm & Safety / Key Technique Tips\n* Keep torso upright — avoid leaning too far forward; core engaged, spine neutral.\n* Front foot should stay flat on floor — distribute weight across entire foot (heel to ball), avoid shifting to toes to protect knees.\n* Knee tracking — ensure the front knee follows same direction as the toes; avoid letting knee collapse inward.\n* Controlled motion — both descent and ascent should be smooth and controlled; avoid bouncing or jerky movements.\n* Balance — if stability is an issue, start bodyweight only; you can hold onto a support (wall or chair) initially or do fewer reps.",
