      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip — ~ 8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym-style or neutral indoor lighting, with clear visibility of barbell, rack, floor and body posture. Use soft key-light + gentle ambient fill so squat depth, torso angle and leg positioning are clearly visible.\n* Sound: Soft gym ambient (barbell weight shifting, floor contact, subtle breath), no voice-over (or optionally soft breath-in / breath-out cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Squat rack or open gym floor with a loaded barbell. Bar set at around shoulder-height in the rack. Floor clear, stable surface, enough space for safe descent and ascent.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) — capturing full body from head to feet, barbell, and motion path (standing → squat → standing) so depth and alignment are visible.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult female, athletic or average build, wearing gym attire (tank or tee + shorts/training pants), preparing to squat with barbell across upper back.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s (Setup / Unrack): Lifter steps under barbell, grips slightly wider than shoulder-width, bar resting on upper back/traps (not neck), stands up and takes a couple of safe steps back from rack. Feet about shoulder-width (or slightly wider), toes slightly outward (~ a small external rotation).\n* 1 s–2 s (Brace & Prepare): Take a deep breath, brace core and glutes, chest up, back neutral (spine straight), eyes forward — prepare for descent.\n* 2 s–4 s (Descent / Lower): Begin squat — push hips back and bend knees/ankles together in a coordinated manner, controlling descent; ensure knees track over toes, heels stay flat (not rising), torso upright, maintain spinal neutrality.\n* 4 s–5 s (Bottom / Hold): At bottom position — ideally thighs at least parallel to floor (or deeper depending on mobility), hips and knees flexed, weight balanced through mid-foot/heels, core tight, chest up. Brief pause (~0.2–0.5 s) to show depth and stability.\n* 5 s–7 s (Ascent / Stand-Up): Drive through heels, extend hips and knees to stand up; keep chest up, back neutral, engage glutes and legs — rising steadily, without bouncing or collapsing.\n* 7 s–8 s (Reset / Finish Pose): Return to upright standing, bar stable on back, posture tall — ready for next rep or end of clip.\nMuscles / Focus\nThe Barbell Squat is a powerful compound exercise engaging multiple muscle groups:\n* Primary movers: Quadriceps (front thighs), Hamstrings, Gluteus maximus (hips / butt) — responsible for knee and hip extension during ascent.\n* Supporting / stabilizing muscles: Core (abs, obliques), spinal erectors (lower back), adductors/hip stabilizers, calves — for balance, posture, stability, and maintaining alignment through the movement.\n* Upper-body (shoulders / back): To stabilize the barbell on the back — upper back, traps, deltoids, arms contribute isometrically to support the load.\nBenefits & Why Use Barbell Squats\n* Squats build lower-body strength — strengthen quads, hamstrings, glutes.\n* They improve core stability, balance and posture — because core and stabilizers have to work to maintain a neutral spine under load.\n* Enhance functional strength and mobility — useful for everyday movements (sitting/standing, lifting, walking), sports, and athletic performance.\n* Efficient full-body exercise — though primarily lower body, the squat activates many muscle groups, providing strength and metabolic stimulus.\nForm & Safety / Key Technique Tips\n* Keep spine neutral — avoid rounding or excessive arching of the back; maintain chest up, head neutral.\n* Feet flat, weight through heels/mid-foot — ensure heels stay grounded throughout the squat; avoid shifting weight onto toes, which can destabilize and strain knees.\n* Knee tracking — knees should track in direction of toes; avoid knee valgus (caving inward) or excessive forward collapse.\n* Control at descent and ascent — avoid bouncing or jerking; smooth, controlled motion maintains muscle engagement and reduces injury risk.\n* Proper bar placement and grip — rest bar on upper back (high-bar) or slightly lower across rear delts (low-bar) depending on comfort and mobility; hands just wider than shoulder-width.\n* Begin with light or no weight if new — master form, mobility, and control before increasing load.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult female, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "The Barbell Squat is a powerful compound exercise engaging multiple muscle groups:\n* Primary movers: Quadriceps (front thighs), Hamstrings, Gluteus maximus (hips / butt) — responsible for knee and hip extension during ascent.\n* Supporting / stabilizing muscles: Core (abs, obliques), spinal erectors (lower back), adductors/hip stabilizers, calves — for balance, posture, stability, and maintaining alignment through the movement.\n* Upper-body (shoulders / back): To stabilize the barbell on the back — upper back, traps, deltoids, arms contribute isometrically to support the load.",
      "benefits": "& Why Use Barbell Squats\n* Squats build lower-body strength — strengthen quads, hamstrings, glutes.\n* They improve core stability, balance and posture — because core and stabilizers have to work to maintain a neutral spine under load.\n* Enhance functional strength and mobility — useful for everyday movements (sitting/standing, lifting, walking), sports, and athletic performance.\n* Efficient full-body exercise — though primarily lower body, the squat activates many muscle groups, providing strength and metabolic stimulus.",
      "safety": "/ Key Technique Tips\n* Keep spine neutral — avoid rounding or excessive arching of the back; maintain chest up, head neutral.\n* Feet flat, weight through heels/mid-foot — ensure heels stay grounded throughout the squat; avoid shifting weight onto toes, which can destabilize and strain knees.\n* Knee tracking — knees should track in direction of toes; avoid knee valgus (caving inward) or excessive forward collapse.\n* Control at descent and ascent — avoid bouncing or jerking; smooth, controlled motion maintains muscle engagement and reduces injury risk.\n* Proper bar placement and grip — rest bar on upper back (high-bar) or slightly lower across rear delts (low-bar) depending on comfort and mobility; hands just wider than shoulder-width.\n* Begin with light or no weight if new — master form, mobility, and control before increasing load."
