      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip — ~ 8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Neutral or gym-style lighting; simple background, minimal distractions; subject in workout clothes; soft key-light + ambient fill to clearly show leg movement, posture and balance\n* Sound: Soft ambient (floor contact, subtle breath, controlled movement), no voice-over (or optional gentle breath cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Open floor space (gym floor, yoga mat, or home space) — stable ground, enough room to step forward and lower without obstruction\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) — capturing full body from head to feet, so that you can see foot placement, torso posture, and depth of lunge\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or average build, wearing workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts/training pants), standing upright, ready to lunge\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0–1 s (Setup): Stand upright with feet about hip-width apart, shoulders back, core engaged, eyes forward. Hands can be at hips or by sides.\n* 1–2 s (Step & Prepare): Take a sufficiently large step forward with one leg (front leg), landing heel first, foot flat; rear foot stays on toes or ball of foot.\n* 2–4 s (Descent / Lunge Down): Bend both knees to lower body — front knee bending until front thigh is near parallel to floor (or as comfort/mobility allows), rear knee lowering toward ground without touching; torso remains mostly upright, core stable, back neutral.\n* 4–5 s (Bottom / Hold): Pause briefly (~0.2–0.5 s) at bottom — feel stretch/activation in front leg, glute/hip, maintain balance and posture.\n* 5–7 s (Ascent / Return): Push through heel/entire foot of front leg, drive hips upward and return to standing position; rear foot moves forward to meet front, resetting stance. Keep movement controlled, avoid rushing.\n* 7–8 s (Reset / Ready): Stand upright again, posture stable, ready for next repetition or clip end\nPrimary Muscles / Focus\nLunges work multiple muscle groups in the lower body and supporting structures:\n* Quadriceps (front thigh) — primary for knee extension during ascent.\n* Gluteal muscles (especially gluteus maximus, also gluteus medius/minimus for hip stability) — engage strongly to control descent and power ascent.\n* Hamstrings and adductors — assist in hip stabilization and knee/hip control, especially when stepping and lowering.\n* Calves and lower-leg stabilizers — help balance and maintain foot/ankle stability during the lunge.\n* Core and trunk stabilizers (abdominals, lower-back) — engaged to keep torso upright, maintain balance and prevent unwanted lean/rotation.\nBenefits & Purpose of Lunge\n* Effective for unilateral leg strength — since each leg works independently, lunges help address side-to-side imbalances.\n* Builds overall lower-body strength and develops glutes, quads, hamstrings — good for functional strength, sports, everyday movement.\n* Enhances balance, stability, and mobility — the stepping and balance challenge engages stabilizer muscles and improves coordination.\n* Useful even without equipment — can be done bodyweight; adding weights (dumbbells, barbell) increases resistance for strength/hypertrophy goals.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Keep torso upright or slightly forward, not hunched — maintain neutral spine and engaged core.\n* Ensure front knee tracks over foot, not collapsing inward; avoid excessive forward knee travel that stresses the knee joint.\n* Step far enough, but not too far — ensure stable stance so front thigh can go near parallel when lowering, and rear leg remains stable.\n* Lower and rise in a controlled manner — avoid dropping quickly or bouncing; control descent and ascent to maximize muscle engagement and reduce injury risk.\n* Use appropriate range of motion and load — especially if you add weights; start with bodyweight to master form before increasing resistance.",
