      "id": "legs_front_barbell_squat_male",
      "name": "Front barbell squat",
      "gender": "male",
      "category": "legs",
      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip — around 8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym-style lighting (barbell, rack, floor visible), neutral background or softly blurred gym-floor; soft key light + subtle fill to highlight torso posture, bar placement, leg movement\n* Sound: Quiet gym ambient (foot placement, barbell clank, breathing), no voice-over (or optionally gentle breath-in / breath-out cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Squat rack or power rack with a barbell loaded; stable floor, enough space in front/back for safe descent/ascent.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or at waist height) — captures full body (head to feet), barbell, bar path, leg and foot position, so squat depth and posture are visible.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or typical build, wearing gym clothes (tank/tee + training pants), ready under bar, with proper grip and bar on front-rack position.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s — Setup / Unrack & Stance: Subject steps under barbell; bar rests across the front of the shoulders/clavicles (front-rack). Hands grip bar slightly wider than shoulder-width; elbows high (parallel or angled slightly upward), chest tall, eyes forward. Step back from rack, feet about shoulder-width (or slightly wider), toes slightly turned out.\n* 1 s–2 s — Brace & Prepare: Take a deep breath, brace core, engage glutes, keep spine neutral, chest up — maintain upright torso, shoulder blades tight to support the bar.\n* 2 s–4 s — Descent / Lowering Phase: Push hips back slightly and bend knees/ankles — descend into squat while keeping torso upright. Lower until thighs are at least parallel to floor (or lower, depending on mobility), heels flat, knees tracking over toes.\n* 4 s–5 s — Bottom / Hold: Pause briefly (~0.2–0.5 s) at bottom to show depth — chest up, core tight, elbows high, weight balanced through mid-foot/heel.\n* 5 s–7 s — Ascent / Stand-up: Drive through heels and mid-foot, extend knees and hips, rise to standing. Maintain upright torso, keep bar stable on front of shoulders, glutes and legs engaged.\n* 7 s–8 s — Reset / Finish: Return to full upright position, stable posture, bar settled; chest up, core engaged — ready for next rep or fade-out.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus (What Front Squat Works)\nFront squats activate a broad group of lower-body and supporting muscles:\n* Quadriceps (quads): Because of the more upright torso and front-load, quads get major emphasis.\n* Glutes & hamstrings (posterior chain): They assist in hip extension and stabilization, supporting the squat motion.\n* Core & spinal stabilizers (abdominals, erector spinae): The front position of the bar demands strong core and back engagement to keep posture upright and prevent the torso from collapsing forward under load.\n* Upper-back / shoulders / traps: Because the bar rests on the front rack (shoulders/clavicles) rather than upper back, upper-body stability (shoulders, traps, upper back muscles) plays a significant role to keep the bar secure and torso upright.\nBenefits & Why Use Front Squat\n* Greater emphasis on quad development and strong lower-body strength with less spinal compression compared to back squat — good for those concerned about lower-back strain.\n* Enhanced core and upper-back strength and posture — because front-rack requires more core/bracing and upper-body stability, helps in improving posture and trunk control.\n* Improved mobility and flexibility — front squat demands good ankle, hip, wrist/shoulder mobility; over time this can enhance joint mobility and functional movement quality.\n* Good functional strength, athletic carryover and balance — builds strength, control, and power that translate to real-life movements and athletic tasks (jumping, running, lifting).\nForm & Safety / Key Technique Tips\n* Use a front-rack grip/placement: Bar should rest on the shoulders/clavicles (not throat), elbows high, upper-back tight — this ensures bar stability and upright posture.\n* Maintain upright torso and neutral spine: Because load is in front, leaning forward will shift load and stress on lower back — keep chest up, core braced, eyes forward.\n* Keep full foot contact — mid-foot/heels grounded, weight evenly distributed (not on toes), knees tracking over toes to avoid knee valgus or undue stress.\n* Start gradually — if you’re new, master bodyweight squat and mobility, then progress to lighter loads or goblet squat before heavy front-barbell squat.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "(What Front Squat Works)\nFront squats activate a broad group of lower-body and supporting muscles:\n* Quadriceps (quads): Because of the more upright torso and front-load, quads get major emphasis.\n* Glutes & hamstrings (posterior chain): They assist in hip extension and stabilization, supporting the squat motion.\n* Core & spinal stabilizers (abdominals, erector spinae): The front position of the bar demands strong core and back engagement to keep posture upright and prevent the torso from collapsing forward under load.\n* Upper-back / shoulders / traps: Because the bar rests on the front rack (shoulders/clavicles) rather than upper back, upper-body stability (shoulders, traps, upper back muscles) plays a significant role to keep the bar secure and torso upright.",
      "benefits": "& Why Use Front Squat\n* Greater emphasis on quad development and strong lower-body strength with less spinal compression compared to back squat — good for those concerned about lower-back strain.\n* Enhanced core and upper-back strength and posture — because front-rack requires more core/bracing and upper-body stability, helps in improving posture and trunk control.\n* Improved mobility and flexibility — front squat demands good ankle, hip, wrist/shoulder mobility; over time this can enhance joint mobility and functional movement quality.\n* Good functional strength, athletic carryover and balance — builds strength, control, and power that translate to real-life movements and athletic tasks (jumping, running, lifting).",
      "safety": "/ Key Technique Tips\n* Use a front-rack grip/placement: Bar should rest on the shoulders/clavicles (not throat), elbows high, upper-back tight — this ensures bar stability and upright posture.\n* Maintain upright torso and neutral spine: Because load is in front, leaning forward will shift load and stress on lower back — keep chest up, core braced, eyes forward.\n* Keep full foot contact — mid-foot/heels grounded, weight evenly distributed (not on toes), knees tracking over toes to avoid knee valgus or undue stress.\n* Start gradually — if you’re new, master bodyweight squat and mobility, then progress to lighter loads or goblet squat before heavy front-barbell squat."
