      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip — ~ 8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym-style lighting — machine visible, neutral or slightly dark floor, subject in standard workout clothes; use soft key-light + subtle ambient fill to highlight legs, machine pad, and motion path\n* Sound: Gym ambient (machine pads, slight metal/weight-stack noise, subtle breathing), no voice-over (or optional soft inhale/exhale cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym leg-curl machine (lying or seated version) or a properly configured hamstring curl machine; floor clear, machine pad and setup adjusted correctly.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or waist-level) capturing from upper torso to feet — enough to clearly show leg movement, pad placement, hip/back posture, and knee motion.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or typical build; wearing gym attire (tank or tee + shorts/leggings), positioned appropriately on machine (lying face-down or seated depending on variation), ready to perform curl.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s — Setup: Subject lies prone (for lying leg-curl) or sits (for seated leg-curl), with ankles secured under the padded roller/lever. Torso stable, legs extended, toes relaxed or slightly flexed, core and hips pressed flat against bench/pad.\n* 1 s–2 s — Brace: Grip handles / hold side supports for stability; engage core, ensure hips stay pinned, prepare to curl.\n* 2 s–4 s — Curl / Concentric Phase: Exhale; flex knees and pull heels toward buttocks by contracting hamstrings, bringing pads toward glutes until maximum comfortable bend. Elbows/arms remain stationary, upper body stays stable.\n* 4 s–5 s — Peak / Hold: At top of curl, pause ~0.2–0.5 seconds — hold position, squeeze hamstrings, ensure no hip lift, maintain stable torso.\n* 5 s–7 s — Lower / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; slowly extend legs back to starting position under control, fully straightening knees, allowing hamstrings to lengthen/stretch; avoid locking out abruptly or letting pads drop.\n* 7 s–8 s — Reset / Ready: Legs extended, body stable, ankles and hips positioned correctly — ready for next rep or clip end.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus\n* Hamstrings: the primary target — including the multiple hamstring muscles at the back of the thigh (e.g. biceps femoris, semitendinosus, semimembranosus).\n* Secondary: Some activation of calf muscles (because of knee flexion movement), and minimal glute involvement (especially when hip remains fixed).\nBenefits of Leg Curl\n* Effective for isolating hamstrings — unlike compound movements (squats, deadlifts) where many muscles are involved, leg curl isolates knee-flexion function to focus solely on hamstrings.\n* Helps balance leg musculature — strengthens posterior chain (hamstrings) which is often neglected when front-dominant leg exercises (like squats) are prioritized; helps reduce quad-to-hamstring strength imbalance and may lower risk of knee/hamstring injuries.\n* Less stress on lower back compared to heavy hip-hinge or squat movements — since upper body remains supported/stabilized on machine, making it a safer hamstring-focused option.\n* Useful for hypertrophy, strength, and rehabilitation — leg curl can be used to build hamstring size and strength, or as controlled rehab/maintenance when heavy lifts might not be advisable.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Keep hips and torso stable — don’t let hips lift or back arch during curl; press hips firmly against bench/pad to isolate hamstrings.\n* Use full range of motion — curl until heels approach glutes (without undue discomfort); fully extend knees on eccentric to maximize stretch; avoid short-range only reps.\n* Control both concentric and eccentric phases — avoid bouncing or jerking; maintain smooth, controlled motion at both upward curl and downward return for maximal muscle tension and lower injury risk.\n* Moderate weight, strict form — use a weight that allows clean form; going too heavy often causes hip lift or momentum, reducing hamstring isolation and increasing risk.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "* Hamstrings: the primary target — including the multiple hamstring muscles at the back of the thigh (e.g. biceps femoris, semitendinosus, semimembranosus).\n* Secondary: Some activation of calf muscles (because of knee flexion movement), and minimal glute involvement (especially when hip remains fixed).",
      "benefits": "of Leg Curl\n* Effective for isolating hamstrings — unlike compound movements (squats, deadlifts) where many muscles are involved, leg curl isolates knee-flexion function to focus solely on hamstrings.\n* Helps balance leg musculature — strengthens posterior chain (hamstrings) which is often neglected when front-dominant leg exercises (like squats) are prioritized; helps reduce quad-to-hamstring strength imbalance and may lower risk of knee/hamstring injuries.\n* Less stress on lower back compared to heavy hip-hinge or squat movements — since upper body remains supported/stabilized on machine, making it a safer hamstring-focused option.\n* Useful for hypertrophy, strength, and rehabilitation — leg curl can be used to build hamstring size and strength, or as controlled rehab/maintenance when heavy lifts might not be advisable.",
      "safety": "/ Technique Tips\n* Keep hips and torso stable — don’t let hips lift or back arch during curl; press hips firmly against bench/pad to isolate hamstrings.\n* Use full range of motion — curl until heels approach glutes (without undue discomfort); fully extend knees on eccentric to maximize stretch; avoid short-range only reps.\n* Control both concentric and eccentric phases — avoid bouncing or jerking; maintain smooth, controlled motion at both upward curl and downward return for maximal muscle tension and lower injury risk.\n* Moderate weight, strict form — use a weight that allows clean form; going too heavy often causes hip lift or momentum, reducing hamstring isolation and increasing risk."
