      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength/mobility clip — ~ 8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym or home-gym floor (or plain studio floor), neutral/dark floor or mat, subject in workout clothes; soft key-light + ambient fill so posture and leg movement are clear\n* Sound: Soft ambient (floor contact, subtle breath, minimal background noise), no voice-over — optionally gentle breathing cues\nScene Setup\n* Location: Open floor space with enough width (side-to-side) so you can step out laterally with one leg. Clear area so foot travel is unobstructed.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) capturing full body from head to feet — showing stance, leg positions, hip and knee motion, and torso alignment.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or normal build, wearing workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts/ pants), standing initially upright, ready to lunge sideways.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0–1 s (Setup): Stand upright with feet about hip- to shoulder-width apart, toes pointing forward or slightly outward, core engaged, chest up, back neutral. Hands may be at hips or in front of chest.\n* 1–2 s (Side Step): Take a wide step laterally (to the side) with one leg — for example step the left leg wide to the left — while keeping toes pointing forward and feet flat on the floor.\n* 2–4 s (Descent / Lunge Down): Bend the knee of the stepping leg and push hips back & down, keeping the other (non-stepping) leg straight (or slightly bent), while lowering into a side-lunge. Keep your torso upright, chest up, back neutral. Heel of stepping leg should stay flat.\n* 4–5 s (Bottom / Hold): Pause ~0.2–0.5 s at the bottom of the lunge; feel stretch in inner thigh / hip of the straight leg, muscles engaged on stepping side (quad, glute, hamstring, adductor). Stabilize core, ensure balance.\n* 5–7 s (Ascent / Return): Push through the heel/foot of the bent (stepping) leg, drive hips up, straighten knee and return to initial standing position — feet hip-width apart. Maintain posture and control.\n* 7–8 s (Reset / Ready): Stand upright, stable posture, ready for next rep or alternate to other side.\nMuscles / Focus (What Side Lunge Works)\n* Primary: Quadriceps (front of thigh), Glutes (gluteus maximus, medius, minimus), Hamstrings.\n* Inner-thigh / Adductors: The straight leg’s inner thigh gets stretched and works to stabilize — good for adductor strength and hip/groin flexibility.\n* Core & Stabilizers: Core (abs/obliques), hip and trunk stabilizers help maintain balance and torso stability, especially during lateral movement.\n* Calves & Lower-leg stabilizers: Work to maintain balance and foot stability during side step and lunge.\nBenefits & Purpose\n* Improves lateral strength, hip mobility, and flexibility — engages muscles often neglected by only forward/backward movements (quads/glutes/adductors) and aids hip mobility.\n* Enhances balance and stability — unilateral, lateral movement requires stabilizer muscles in legs, hips, core to coordinate, improving muscle-balance and functional movement.\n* Targets inner-thigh/adductor muscles + glutes/outer hips — good supplemental exercise alongside squats/deadlifts to develop full leg musculature and reduce imbalance.\n* Useful for mobility, injury prevention, and functional fitness — training through lateral plane helps with real-world movements (side-to-side, changes of direction), reduces risk of overuse injuries, and improves joint health (hips, knees).\nForm & Technique / Key Safety Tips\n* Keep torso upright and spine neutral — avoid leaning too far forward; chest up, core engaged.\n* Ensure knee tracks over toes — bent leg’s knee should not collapse inward or go way past toes; heel of that foot should stay flat for stability.\n* Use a proper step width — step wide enough to comfortably lunge laterally and get stretch, but avoid overstretching which might overstrain groin/hip.\n* Perform controlled, smooth motion — avoid bouncing or jerky movement; descent and ascent under control for joint safety and muscle activation.\n* Start bodyweight first — especially if new to the movement; once form and balance are stable, you can progress to holding weights (dumbbells, kettlebell) for more resistance.",
