      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip — ~ 8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym lighting (machine metal, padded seat/backrest, clean floor mat), soft key-light + ambient fill to highlight legs, foot-platform, and motion path\n* Sound: Soft ambient (machine sliders/plates, subtle foot-platform pressure, controlled breathing), no commentary (or optionally soft breath-in / breath-out cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Leg-press machine (angled or 45°-sled type, or horizontal depending on gym), seat and backrest adjusted so back & buttocks rest comfortably, safety catches/rails secured. Floor around machine clear.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or at knee level) — captures full lower-body, foot-platform, knees and feet placement, torso/backrest contact, so movement depth and alignment are visible.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, wearing gym clothes (tank/tee + shorts/training pants), seated with back against pad, feet on foot-plate, ready to push.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s (Setup): Subject sits with back & butt firmly against pad/backrest, feet placed shoulder-width (or slightly wider) on platform, knees bent at comfortable angle, heels flat. Hands grip side handles for stability.\n* 1 s–2 s (Brace): Engage core, glutes stable, ensure back stays pressed to pad, check feet alignment (heels flat, toes slightly out if preferred), prepare for movement.\n* 2 s–4 s (Press / Concentric Phase): Exhale and push through feet — extend knees and hips to drive platform away, until legs are almost straight but do not lock out knees fully (to avoid joint stress).\n* 4 s–5 s (Hold / Peak): At near-full extension, hold briefly (~0.2–0.5 s) to show muscle engagement (quads, glutes, hamstrings). Maintain foot contact; do not let hips lift off pad.\n* 5 s–7 s (Return / Eccentric Phase): Inhale and slowly bend knees and hips to return platform toward body — control the descent, keep back flat, avoid letting weight drop or knee collapse inward/outward.\n* 7 s–8 s (Reset / Ready): Knees bent, platform close, back & butt against pad, feet stable — ready for next rep or clip fade-out.\nMuscles / Focus (What Leg Press Works)\nThe leg press primarily targets lower-body muscles:\n* Quadriceps (front thighs) — major load during knee extension.\n* Gluteus maximus (glutes) — via hip extension, especially when foot placement is higher on the platform.\n* Hamstrings — assist in hip/knee control, particularly with adjusted foot placement or deeper press.\n* Calves / lower-leg (to a lesser extent) — engaged via ankle stabilization and extension when pressing.\nBecause your back is supported, the exercise allows focused leg work without much spinal load.\nBenefits & Why Use Leg Press\n* Allows heavy loading of lower-body muscles safely — good for strength and hypertrophy, even if you have lower-back issues or want to minimize spinal load.\n* Offers controlled, stable movement (back supported, fixed plane) — easier to maintain good form than many free-weight movements.\n* Enables muscle-targeting adjustments via foot placement — e.g. higher foot plate emphasis on glutes/hamstrings; lower or narrow placement emphasizes quads.\n* Good for beginners or rehabilitation contexts, or as an accessory for advanced lifters — supplementing free-weight exercises for balanced leg development.\nForm & Safety / Technique & Cautions\n* Ensure back & hips stay flush against the pad — avoid lifting hips off seat at any point (“butt-wink” or hip rising compromises safety).\n* Do not lock out knees fully at top — keep slight bend at knees to avoid joint strain; avoid excessive speed or bouncing.\n* Use foot placement and stance carefully depending on your goal — for quads, lower & narrower; for glutes/hamstrings, higher & wider.\n* Control both pressing and return phases — avoid letting weight slam down or pushing too fast; smooth tempo helps muscle engagement and reduces injury risk.\n* Choose appropriate weight — it’s tempting to overload since body is supported; ensure you can maintain control, range of motion, and proper form.",
