      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional clip — ~ 6–8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym lighting or neutral indoor lighting; machine clearly visible, minimal background distractions; subtle key-light + ambient fill to highlight legs, pad, and motion.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (machine pads sliding, subtle breath, minimal background noise), no voice-over (or optional soft breathing cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Leg-extension machine in a gym (or home-gym with a machine). Seat and back-pad adjusted for subject’s leg length; shin pad positioned correctly. Floor clear, machine stable.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) — captures from waist down to feet, showing seat, pad, leg motion, knee angle, and foot-plate/foot orientation.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, wearing workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts/training pants), seated upright, back pressed against back-pad, feet under pad, ready to extend legs.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0–1 s (Setup): Subject sits with back firmly against back-pad. Knees bent at ~90°, shins under padded lever just above ankles, feet facing forward. Hands grip side handles or seat edges for stability.\n* 1–2 s (Brace): Engage core, keep torso and hips stable against pad, ensure correct pad alignment (knee joint aligned with machine pivot).\n* 2–4 s (Extension / Concentric Phase): Exhale; extend knees, lifting pad upward by straightening legs until knees are nearly locked out (leg nearly straight — but avoid hyper-extending or locking hard).\n* 4–5 s (Peak Hold): At full extension, pause ~0.2–0.5 s — squeeze quadriceps, feel contraction in front-thigh muscles.\n* 5–7 s (Return / Eccentric): Inhale; slowly bend knees back under control, lowering pad and returning to start position; avoid letting weight drop uncontrolled.\n* 7–8 s (Reset / Ready): Legs bent, back stable, ready for next rep or fade-out.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Quadriceps femoris (front-thigh) — including the four heads: rectus femoris, vastus lateralis, vastus medialis, vastus intermedius. The leg-extension isolates these muscles.\n* Secondary / Supporting: Minimal involvement of other leg muscles — because this is a single-joint, isolation exercise; main focus remains quads.\nBenefits & Purpose\n* Quad isolation & hypertrophy: Helps build strength and size of quadriceps effectively, especially useful if you want well-defined front thighs.\n* Knee joint & knee-extensor strength: Strengthening quads supports knee stability and function (important for walking, running, jumping, daily activities).\n* Lower spinal load: Because you sit and torso remains stable, the exercise imposes minimal stress on the spine — safer for those with back concerns compared to heavy compound lifts.\n* Isolation / Finisher or Pre-exhaust: It can be used to “pre-exhaust” quads before compound leg work, or as a finisher to burn out the quads at end of leg day.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Align the machine pivot with your knee joint — ensures natural movement and reduces undue stress on joints.\n* Back and hips pressed firmly against pad — avoid raising or shifting hips during extension, to maintain isolation and spine safety.\n* Use controlled motion — both extension and return (eccentric) should be smooth and deliberate; avoid dropping weight quickly or using momentum.\n* Avoid locking knees forcefully at top — stop just short of full lockout to reduce joint strain, especially if using heavy weight or many reps.\n* Choose appropriate, moderate weight — too heavy a load may stress knees or cause compensation; better to use manageable resistance for full range and clean form.",
