      "muscles": "(What Sumo Squat Works)\nThe sumo squat is a compound lower-body exercise that emphasizes several muscle groups — with added stress on inner thighs and hip/glute region compared to a standard squat.\n* Primary movers:\n* Quadriceps (front thigh) — responsible for knee extension during ascent.\n* Gluteus maximus and gluteus medius/minimus (butt / hips) — major contributors during hip extension and rise from bottom.\n* Inner-thigh / Adductor muscles (inner thigh) — more engaged in sumo stance than in conventional squat, due to wide stance and outward foot angle.\n* Supporting / stabilizing muscles:\n* Hamstrings and hips — assist in stability and controlled descent, as well as hip extension on ascent.\n* Core and trunk muscles (abdominals, lower back) — stabilize trunk to maintain upright posture, support spine, especially under load.\n* Calves / lower-leg — help with balance and ankle stability through the movement.",
      "benefits": "& Why Use Sumo Squat\n* Targets inner thighs / adductors — often under-trained in regular squat routines, useful for leg strength balance and hip stability.\n* Strongly engages glutes and hips — promotes hip strength and glute muscle development, helpful for posture, power, and lower-body aesthetics.\n* Lower-body strength & leg development — quad, hamstring, glute and hip strength improves, enhancing functional strength for everyday tasks (lifting, sitting/standing) and athletic movements.\n* Hip mobility and joint flexibility / stability — wide stance and controlled descent may improve hip mobility; adductor activation supports hip/knee stability.\n* Alternative or complement to regular squats — offers variety in lower-body training, and shifts emphasis from standard squat patterns (which often over-emphasize quads) to glutes/adductors + hips.",
      "safety": "/ Key Technique Tips\n* Use a wide enough stance — feet significantly wider than shoulder-width, toes pointed outward (≈ 30–45°) to facilitate proper knee and hip alignment.\n* Keep knees tracking in direction of toes — avoid letting knees cave inward; drive them outward as you descend and ascend to protect joints and engage correct muscles.\n* Weight on heels / mid-foot, heel contact maintained — avoid rising onto toes; ensures balance and proper force distribution, preserves knee/hip safety.\n* Torso upright / spine neutral / core braced — maintain straight back, chest up, avoid excessive leaning forward; engage core and glutes throughout movement for stability and safety.\n* Controlled tempo, smooth motion — both descent and ascent should be steady; avoid bouncing or rapid movements; helps maximize muscle activation and minimize joint stress."
