      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip — ~ 8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym-style lighting (bench visible, barbell with weights), neutral background (gym floor or wall), subject wearing workout clothes; soft key-light + ambient fill to highlight hips, leg and torso alignment\n* Sound: Soft ambient (floor/bench contact, barbell clink, subtle breathing), no voice-over (or optional gentle breath-in / breath-out cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Use a weight bench (flat) or stable elevated surface; place a loaded barbell (with padding if available) on the floor in front of the bench. Floor clear around bench.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) — capturing from head to knees/hips, bench, barbell, and showing full hip motion. Enough to see back position on bench, foot placement, barbell across hips, and extension path.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or average build, wearing gym attire (tank/tee + shorts/training pants), ready to perform hip thrust with barbell.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s — Setup / Positioning: Sit on floor with back against bench (bench edge aligned roughly at mid-upper back / lower scapula). Roll the barbell over shins and legs, so it rests horizontally across hips (just below hip bone / across pelvis). Feet flat on floor, hip-to-shoulder-width apart, knees bent, feet positioned such that when you thrust hips up, knee angle is roughly ~90°. Hands grip bar to stabilize; core engaged.\n* 1 s–2 s — Brace & Stability: Keep upper back firmly against bench pad, core braced, chin slightly tucked or neutral, glutes relaxed but ready to engage. Ensure feet flat, weight evenly distributed through mid-foot/heels.\n* 2 s–4 s — Thrust / Concentric Phase: Drive through heels, extend hips upward — lift pelvis toward ceiling until your body forms a straight line from shoulders to knees (hip extension). Shoulders remain on bench, spine neutral, glutes and hamstrings engaged. Barbell moves upward with hips.\n* 4 s–5 s — Peak / Hold: At full hip extension, pause ~0.2–0.5 seconds; squeeze glutes firmly, hold posture (shoulders on bench, hips high). This is the ‘lockout’ point.\n* 5 s–7 s — Lower / Eccentric Phase: Lower hips back down under control — hips descend until glutes nearly touch floor (or until start position), barbell tracks down accordingly, knees bent, feet flat. Avoid crashing; maintain control and posture.\n* 7 s–8 s — Reset / Ready: Hips down, back against bench, barbell stable, feet solid; breathe, reset posture, ready for next rep or end clip.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus\n* Gluteus maximus (glutes): Primary driver — strongest activation among common lower-body lifts. Barbell Hip Thrust is one of the most effective exercises for glute activation.\n* Hamstrings (back of thigh): Assist in hip extension and stabilization during the thrust.\n* Hip extensors & posterior chain: Because of the horizontal loading and hip-driven movement, hip extensors (glutes, hamstrings) and supporting posterior-chain muscles are engaged effectively.\n* Core & lower-back stabilizers: Support spine and pelvis stability throughout movement — important to prevent lower-back stress and ensure proper hip extension.\nBenefits & Why Use Barbell Hip Thrust\n* Superior glute activation: Compared with many traditional lifts, hip thrusts produce higher glute activation — ideal for developing glute strength, size, and hip-extension power.\n* Improved hip strength and sports performance: Effective for boosting hip extension strength, which translates to better jumping, sprinting, posture, and lower-body power.\n* Lower back–friendly compared to heavy squats/deadlifts: Because the upper back rests on bench and load is horizontally across hips, stress on lumbar spine is reduced — suitable if you want posterior-chain strength without excessive spinal loading.\n* Versatility & progression: You can start with bodyweight or light load and progressively increase barbell weight; also easy to adjust foot placement to emphasize glutes or hamstrings.\nForm & Safety / Key Technique Notes\n* Ensure upper back (shoulders / scapula) firmly rests on bench pad — avoid letting bench move or only lower back contact. This ensures correct hip-pivot and prevents strain.\n* Feet flat, heels grounded, weight through mid-foot/heels — avoid rising onto toes; this provides stable base and proper glute activation.\n* Controlled tempo — both up and down — avoid jerky movements; concentrate on squeezing glutes at top and controlling descent for maximum muscle engagement and safety.\n* Barbell placement and padding — bar should rest across hips/pelvis (not dangerously on soft tissue), ideally with bar pad or towel to avoid discomfort or bruising.\n* Core and pelvic alignment — keep core tight, avoid excessive lumbar arching at top; hips should align so body forms a straight line shoulders-to-knees at lockout.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "* Gluteus maximus (glutes): Primary driver — strongest activation among common lower-body lifts. Barbell Hip Thrust is one of the most effective exercises for glute activation.\n* Hamstrings (back of thigh): Assist in hip extension and stabilization during the thrust.\n* Hip extensors & posterior chain: Because of the horizontal loading and hip-driven movement, hip extensors (glutes, hamstrings) and supporting posterior-chain muscles are engaged effectively.\n* Core & lower-back stabilizers: Support spine and pelvis stability throughout movement — important to prevent lower-back stress and ensure proper hip extension.",
      "benefits": "& Why Use Barbell Hip Thrust\n* Superior glute activation: Compared with many traditional lifts, hip thrusts produce higher glute activation — ideal for developing glute strength, size, and hip-extension power.\n* Improved hip strength and sports performance: Effective for boosting hip extension strength, which translates to better jumping, sprinting, posture, and lower-body power.\n* Lower back–friendly compared to heavy squats/deadlifts: Because the upper back rests on bench and load is horizontally across hips, stress on lumbar spine is reduced — suitable if you want posterior-chain strength without excessive spinal loading.\n* Versatility & progression: You can start with bodyweight or light load and progressively increase barbell weight; also easy to adjust foot placement to emphasize glutes or hamstrings.",
      "safety": "/ Key Technique Notes\n* Ensure upper back (shoulders / scapula) firmly rests on bench pad — avoid letting bench move or only lower back contact. This ensures correct hip-pivot and prevents strain.\n* Feet flat, heels grounded, weight through mid-foot/heels — avoid rising onto toes; this provides stable base and proper glute activation.\n* Controlled tempo — both up and down — avoid jerky movements; concentrate on squeezing glutes at top and controlling descent for maximum muscle engagement and safety.\n* Barbell placement and padding — bar should rest across hips/pelvis (not dangerously on soft tissue), ideally with bar pad or towel to avoid discomfort or bruising.\n* Core and pelvic alignment — keep core tight, avoid excessive lumbar arching at top; hips should align so body forms a straight line shoulders-to-knees at lockout."
