      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional lower-body clip — ~ 8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Neutral or gym / home-gym style lighting; simple background, clear floor space; subject in workout clothes — soft key-light + ambient fill to highlight legs, hip/knee motion, balance.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (floor contact, subtle breath, minimal noise), no voice-over (or optionally soft inhale/exhale cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Open floor space (gym floor, mat, or stable ground) — enough room to safely step and drop; floor uncluttered.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) capturing full body from head to feet — shows stance, foot placement, leg path, torso alignment, and movement fluidity.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or average build, wearing workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts/training pants), ready in upright, neutral-stance position.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup: Subject stands upright with feet together (or hip-width), arms hanging by sides (or on hips), core engaged, chest up, eyes forward.\n* 1–2 s — Step / Drop: Subject steps one leg diagonally backward and slightly outward (or backward across), reaching back as far as comfortable — this is the “drop” step portion. Rear leg shifts back and to side; front leg remains near original location.\n* 2–4 s — Descent / Lunge Phase: Lower into a lunge: bend front knee to ~90°, while rear leg extends behind (rear knee moves toward floor), torso remains upright (or slightly leaning, depending on variation), balance maintained.\n* 4–5 s — Bottom / Hold: Pause briefly (~0.2–0.5 s) at bottom — feel stretch/engagement in front thigh (quadriceps), glute/hip and hamstring of both legs (especially rear). Core remains braced, posture stable.\n* 5–7 s — Drive / Return: Push through heel / mid-foot of front leg, drive hips forward, return to upright starting position; rear leg returns forward — control the movement.\n* 7–8 s — Reset / Ready: Stand upright, reset posture, breathe, prepare for next rep or fade-out.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus\n* Quadriceps — front-leg knee-extension during lunge drives much of the effort.\n* Glutes and Gluteus Maximus / Hip muscles — engaged to control hip extension and support balance, especially when dropping back and returning.\n* Hamstrings and posterior-chain (hip and thigh back side) — especially in rear leg, for stability and control during drop and rise.\n* Core / Stabilizers / Balance muscles — since drop lunge involves a more dynamic, multi-planar movement (rear-ward + sideways drop), core and stabilizer muscles (hips, ankle/foot) work to maintain balance and joint control.\nBenefits & Why Use Drop Lunge\n* Works legs unilateral and functional strength, improving balance, coordination and stability rather than just strength in a fixed plane.\n* Targets glutes, quads, hamstrings, hips — a compound leg exercise that also hits hip-stabilizers and posterior-chain muscles.\n* Useful for training deceleration, directional changes, and joint strength/stability — beneficial for athletes or people seeking functional fitness beyond straight-plane exercises.\n* Because the load is often just bodyweight (or light dumbbells), it's accessible even at home or with minimal equipment, making it suitable for warm-ups or leg days without heavy gear.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Keep core tight and torso upright — avoid excessive forward lean or slouching.\n* Ensure front knee tracks over toes, not collapsing inward or forward beyond toes, to minimize knee stress. Rear leg should reach behind comfortably without over-twisting hip.\n* Maintain balance and control — the drop step and lunge involve directional change, so move deliberately (both descent and return), avoid jerky motions.\n* Start with bodyweight, master movement pattern and balance before adding external load (dumbbell, kettlebell, etc). Overloading can compromise form or stability.",
